'''Benjamin LaShaun Troupe''' (born September 1, 1982) is a former American college and professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[tight end]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for five seasons during the early 2000s.  Troupe played [[college football]] for the [[University of Florida]], and earned [[All-American]] honors.  He was a second-round pick in the [[2004 NFL Draft]], and played professionally for the [[Tennessee Titans]] and [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] of the NFL.

== Early years ==

Troupe was born in [[Swainsboro, Georgia]] in 1982.<ref name=pfrprofile>Pro-Football-reference.com, Players, [http://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/TrouBe00.htm  Ben Troupe].  Retrieved March 19, 2011.</ref>  He attended [[Butler High School (Augusta, Georgia)|Butler High School]] in [[Augusta, Georgia]],<ref name=dbfprofile>databaseFootball.com, Players, [http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=TROUPBEN01  Ben Troupe].  Retrieved March 19, 2011.</ref> where he played [[high school football]] for the Butler Bulldogs.<ref name=ufprofile>Gatorzone.com, Football History, 2003 Roster, [http://web.gatorzone.com/football/bios.php?year=2003&sub=team&bio=troupe.html  Ben Troupe].  Retrieved March 19, 2011.</ref>  Following his senior season, Troupe was a PrepStar high school [[All-American]] and was recognized by the ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' as one of the top four tight end prospects in the Southeast.<ref name=ufprofile/> [[San Francisco 49ers]] [[cornerback]] [[Carlos Rogers (American football)|Carlos Rogers]] was one of Troupe's Bulldog teammates.

== College career ==

Troupe received an [[athletic scholarship]] to attend the University of Florida in [[Gainesville, Florida]], where he played for coach [[Steve Spurrier]] and coach [[Ron Zook]]'s [[Florida Gators football]] teams from [[2000 Florida Gators football team|2000]] to [[2003 Florida Gators football team|2003]].<ref name=ufmediaguide>''[http://web.gatorzone.com/football/media/2011/media_guide.pdf  2011 Florida Gators Football Media Guide]'', University Athletic Association, Gainesville, Florida, pp. 89, 97, 101, 143&ndash;145, 186 (2011).  Retrieved August 31, 2011.</ref>  He finished his college career with sixty-four [[Reception (American football)|reception]]s for 958 yards (14.9 yards per catch) and seven [[touchdown]]s.<ref name=ufprofile/>  As a senior [[captain (sports)|team captain]] in 2003, Troupe was a first team All-[[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) selection and received first-team All-American honors from [[ESPN]], [[Rivals.com]] and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.<ref name=ufmediaguide/>  He was also one of three finalists for the [[John Mackey Award]], recognizing the nation's best college tight end in 2003.<ref name=ufmediaguide/>

== Professional career ==

The [[Tennessee Titans]] selected Troupe in the second round (fortieth choice overall) of the 2004 NFL Draft.<ref>Pro Football Hall of Fame, Draft History, [http://www.profootballhof.com/history/story.aspx?story_id=2041  2004 National Football League Draft].  Retrieved March 19, 2011.</ref>  He played tight end for the Titans from {{NFL Year|2004}} to {{NFL Year|2007}},<ref name=nflprofile>National Football League, Historical Players, [http://www.nfl.com/players/bentroupe/profile?id=TRO531860  Ben Troupe].  Retrieved March 19, 2011.</ref> and was nicknamed "Troupe Scadoop" by his Titans teammates.  During his four seasons with the Titans, he made 106 [[reception (American football)|reception]]s for 1,056 yards and seven touchdowns.<ref name=nflprofile/>

Troupe signed with the Tampa Bay Buccaneers on March 6, 2008.  He was released on September 16, after Buccaneers [[tight end]] [[Jerramy Stevens]] returned from suspension.  Three days after his release from the Buccaneers, Troupe was signed by the [[Oakland Raiders]].  He was placed on injured reserve with a foot injury on October 21, and released by the Raiders on November 17.

== Life after football ==

Troupe is currently a regular weekly guest on B.J. Bennett's "Afternoon Drive" radio show on Wednesdays between 5-7 p.m.  The show is broadcast on [[ESPN Radio]] 103.7 FM &ndash; 790 AM from [[Brunswick, Georgia]].

